Types of Risks in Risk Management Strategy
1. Credit Risk
‚Ä¢ 	Impact:
‚Ä¢ 	Losses due to borrowers or counterparties failing to meet obligations.
‚Ä¢ 	Can lead to defaults, reduced profitability, and reputational damage.
‚Ä¢ 	Methods of Reducing Impact:
‚Ä¢ 	Diversification of loan portfolios.
‚Ä¢ 	Credit scoring and rating systems.
‚Ä¢ 	Collateral and guarantees.
‚Ä¢ 	Regular monitoring of borrower financial health.
‚Ä¢ 	Quantification:
‚Ä¢ 	Probability of Default (PD): Likelihood borrower will default.
‚Ä¢ 	Loss Given Default (LGD): Expected loss if default occurs.
‚Ä¢ 	Exposure at Default (EAD): Total value at risk.
‚Ä¢ 	Combined into Expected Loss (EL = PD √ó LGD √ó EAD).

2. Liquidity Risk
‚Ä¢ 	Impact:
‚Ä¢ 	Inability to meet short-term obligations due to insufficient liquid assets.
‚Ä¢ 	Can trigger insolvency, forced asset sales, or regulatory breaches.
‚Ä¢ 	Methods of Reducing Impact:
‚Ä¢ 	Maintaining adequate cash reserves.
‚Ä¢ 	Establishing committed credit lines.
‚Ä¢ 	Stress testing under adverse scenarios.
‚Ä¢ 	Asset-liability management (ALM) to balance maturities.
‚Ä¢ 	Quantification:
‚Ä¢ 	Liquidity Coverage Ratio (LCR): High-quality liquid assets vs. net cash outflows.
‚Ä¢ 	Net Stable Funding Ratio (NSFR): Stable funding vs. required funding.
‚Ä¢ 	Gap analysis of inflows vs. outflows.

3. Legal Risk
‚Ä¢ 	Impact:
‚Ä¢ 	Losses from unenforceable contracts, regulatory penalties, or litigation.
‚Ä¢ 	Can damage reputation and lead to financial sanctions.
‚Ä¢ 	Methods of Reducing Impact:
‚Ä¢ 	Strong compliance frameworks.
‚Ä¢ 	Regular legal audits and contract reviews.
‚Ä¢ 	Clear documentation and adherence to jurisdictional laws.
‚Ä¢ 	Insurance coverage for litigation risks.
‚Ä¢ 	Quantification:
‚Ä¢ 	Difficult to measure precisely; often assessed via:
‚Ä¢ 	Scenario analysis (estimating potential fines/lawsuits).
‚Ä¢ 	Historical loss data from legal disputes.
‚Ä¢ 	Provisioning for contingent liabilities.

